'''Shiogama Shrine''' (しおがまじんじゃ) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in central {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakayama Prefecture|qq=}}{{ill|Wakayama City|ja|和歌山市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakayama City|qq=}}{{ill|Wakaura|ja|和歌浦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakaura|qq=}}. It is also written as 鹽竈神社.

== History ==
In {{ill|1917|ja|1917|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1917|qq=}} (the 6th year of {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō|qq=}}), Shiogama Shrine became a shrine emerging from the {{ill|Purification Hall|ja|祓所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Purification Hall|qq=}} of {{ill|Tamatsushima Shrine|ja|玉津島神社|lt=Tamatsushima Shrine|lt_ja=玉津嶋神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamatsushima Shrine|qq=}}. It is a shrine venerated as the deity of seafood and safe childbirth, and the {{ill|Sacred Object|ja|神体|1=Shintai|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sacred Object|13=User:Immanuelle/Shintai|qq=}} of {{ill|Shiotsuchi no Oji|ja|シオツチノオジ|lt=Salt Hammer Elder|lt_ja=塩槌翁尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiotsuchi no Oji|qq=}} is enshrined in a rock cave known as '''Palanquin Cave'''.

It is located on the southern face of Kagami Mountain, which is composed of crystalline schist. The exposed rock surface, displaying a texture reminiscent of raw wood grain, is called Kyara Rock, and the interplay of rock and pine trees preserves the original landscape of Tamatsushima. The subsidiary shrine is a cave naturally formed by the sea breeze. Inside the cave, a small worship hall has been constructed. Originally, it served as an auxiliary space of {{ill|Tamatsushima Shrine|ja|玉津島神社|lt=Tamatsushima Shrine|lt_ja=玉津嶋神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamatsushima Shrine|qq=}}, and was known as “Koshi no Iwaya” (こしのいわや). The name derives from the fact that, in the past, during the beach descent ritual, the portable shrine was placed there.

Hamafuri is a ritual in which, every {{ill|September 16|ja|9月16日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/September 16|qq=}}, the portable shrine of the land deity Amano from {{ill|Nibu Tohime Shrine|ja|丹生都比売神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nibu Tohime Shrine|qq=}} of {{ill|Koyasan|ja|高野山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koyasan|qq=}} traverses along the {{ill|Kino River|ja|紀の川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kino River|qq=}} all the way to {{ill|Tamatsushima Shrine|ja|玉津島神社|lt=Tamatsushima Shrine|lt_ja=玉津嶋神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamatsushima Shrine|qq=}}, and on the following day proceeds to {{ill|Nichijingu|ja|日前神宮・國懸神宮|lt=Nichijingu|lt_ja=日前宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nichijingu|qq=}} as part of the ritual, with the location where the portable shrine was enshrined overnight at Tamatsushima Shrine being known as “Koshi no Iwaya”.

The Hamafuri ritual is believed to date back to ancient times, although it was temporarily suspended during the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}}, and records show that it was resumed in {{ill|Bunpō|ja|文保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunpō|qq=}} 2 ({{ill|1318|ja|1318|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1318|qq=}}). Thereafter, it ceased during the Sengoku period, and in later times it evolved into a ritual in which worshippers paid homage to Tamatsushima Shrine from outside the torii of Amano Shrine. However, the faith in this cave was not limited to the Hamafuri ritual; in the late {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, it was venerated under the name “Shiokama”. In Edo period Wakayama, a verse was sung:
„First, Gongen ({{ill|Kishū Tōshō-gū|ja|紀州東照宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishū Tōshō-gū|qq=}}),
second, Tamatsushima,
third, Descending Pine,
fourth, Shiogama.”
It is said that this name was derived from a salt kiln used to fire salt from the salt fields. It is also believed that the site has long been enshrined as the guardian deity of safe childbirth; even today, it is cherished as a protector of safe childbirth.

On a small hill near the shrine stands a famous song monument of {{ill|Yamabe Akito|ja|山部赤人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamabe Akito|qq=}}, as if overlooking the tidal flats.<ref>In June 2012, the song monument and an adjacent ancient tree—“Wagō no Matsu”, a tree several hundred years old—collapsed (see “Collapse of the ‘Wagō no Matsu’ due to termite damage”, MSN Sankei News, published on June 24, 2012). There are currently voices calling for the regeneration of the old pine.</ref> Nearby, there once stood the venerable “Wagō no Matsu”, an ancient tree that had gathered the faith of many as the guardian deity of domestic harmony, but it collapsed in June {{ill|2012|ja|2012|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2012|qq=}} (the 24th year of the {{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heisei|qq=}} period). In an effort to revive its form—a symbol of Wakayura—a cloned sapling produced from cuttings, a method generally considered difficult, was planted in its original location in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.wakayamashimpo.co.jp/2018/04/20180419_78642.html|title=２世の苗木を植樹へ　塩竃神社「和合の松」2018th year 4月19日|accessdate=2018th year 9月3日|publisher=わかやま新報|language=ja}}</ref>

The entire area, including the shrine, is designated as part of the national {{ill|Historic Site|ja|史跡|1=Historic site|lt=Historic site of Japan|3=史跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Historic Site|13=User:Immanuelle/Historic site|qq=}} and {{ill|Scenic Spot|ja|名勝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Scenic Spot|qq=}} area of {{ill|Wakaura|ja|和歌浦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakaura|qq=}}.
[[ja:塩竈神社 (和歌山市)]]

