On a small hill near the shrine stands a famous song monument of [[:en:Yamabe no Akahito|Yamabe Akito]], as if overlooking the tidal flats.<ref>In June 2012, the song monument and an adjacent ancient tree—“Wagō no Matsu”, a tree several hundred years old—collapsed (see “Collapse of the ‘Wagō no Matsu’ due to termite damage”, MSN Sankei News, published on June 24, 2012). There are currently voices calling for the regeneration of the old pine.</ref> Nearby, there once stood the venerable “Wagō no Matsu”, an ancient tree that had gathered the faith of many as the guardian deity of domestic harmony, but it collapsed in June {{ill|2012|ja|2012|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2012|qq=}} (the 24th year of the [[:en:Heisei era|Heisei]] period). In an effort to revive its form—a symbol of Wakayura—a cloned sapling produced from cuttings, a method generally considered difficult, was planted in its original location in April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.wakayamashimpo.co.jp/2018/04/20180419_78642.html|title=２世の苗木を植樹へ 塩竃神社「和合の松」2018th year 4月19日|accessdate=2018th year 9月3日|publisher=わかやま新報|language=ja}}</ref>
The entire area, including the shrine, is designated as part of the national [[:en:Historic site|Historic site of Japan]] and {{ill|Scenic Spot|ja|名勝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Scenic Spot|qq=}} area of {{ill|Wakaura|ja|和歌浦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakaura|qq=}}. [[ja:塩竈神社 (和歌山市)]]
== Grounds == * Main Hall – called '''Palanquin Cave''' * Worship Hall
